Storms that formed in the central Pacific are given names from a sequential list; in 2006, the name ''[[Hurricane Ioke|Ioke]]'' was used from this list, the first time a name from the Central Pacific list had been used since the [[2002 Pacific hurricane season|2002 season]].

===Retirement===
The name ''Ioke'' was [[List of retired Pacific hurricane names|retired]] from the north-central Pacific list by the [[World Meteorological Organization|WMO]] in the spring of 2007 and replaced with Iopa.<ref>{{cite web|author=Dennis H. McCarthy|year=2007|title=National Weather Service Instruction Tropical Cyclone Names and Pronunciation Guide|accessdate=2007-12-29|url=http://www.weather.gov/directives/sym/pd01006006curr.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> During the 61st Interdepartmental Hurricane Conference, the Hawaii State Civil Defense requested the retirement of the name ''Daniel'', citing that the storm had become memorable due to threat or damage.<ref>{{cite web|author=Interdepartmental Hurricane Conference|year=2007|title=The Nation<U+2019>s Hurricane Program: An Interagency Success Story|accessdate=2007-12-29|url=http://www.ofcm.gov/ihc07/web-61st-IHC-Booklet.pdf|format=PDF}}</ref> However, the request was denied, as the name remains on the tropical cyclone naming list.<ref name="name"/>

